metadata.name: Dotwork #211
metadata.description:
A Cellular Dice Piece

Computational modeling is the use of computers to simulate and study complex systems using mathematics, physics and computer science. A computational model contains numerous variables that characterize the system being studied. Simulation is done by adjusting the variables alone or in combination and observing the outcomes. Computer modeling allows scientists to conduct thousands of simulated experiments by computer. The thousands of computer experiments identify the handful of laboratory experiments that are most likely to solve the problem being studied.

Today's sociocultural discourse might obscure the fact that humanity has been using artificial modeling techniques since ancient times. Permutations, calculus, algorithms are not exclusive to our time, but these are ubiquituous methods that can be found in many cultural entities where members of the community progress and develop their environment through cooperative decisions and consensus. Since computers were not available in the past, calculation methods, application of chance, randomness and probability were performed using other methods, like dices, sticks, cards, weather, rituals or other manifestations.

Dice are small, throwable objects with marked sides that can rest in multiple positions. They are used for generating random numbers, commonly as part of tabletop games, including dice games, board games, role-playing games, and games of chance. A traditional die is a cube with each of its six faces marked with a different number of dots (pips) from one to six. When thrown or rolled, the die comes to rest showing a random integer from one to six on its upper surface, with each value being equally likely. These tools were often used when a decision required to outsource human subjective elements into an objective environment.

Divination can be seen as a systematic method with which to organize what appears to be disjointed, random facets of existence such that they provide insight into a problem at hand. If a distinction is to be made between divination and fortune-telling, divination has a more formal or ritualistic element and often contains a more social character, usually in a religious context, as seen in traditional African medicine. Divination has long been criticized. In the modern era, it has been dismissed by the scientific community and skeptics as being superstitious; experiments do not support the idea that divination techniques can actually predict the future more reliably or precisely than would be possible without it.

This idea is especially adaptable to the data driven belief systems of our time, where human decision making involves trust in omnipresent although obscure and biased artificial intelligence, esoteric pattern analysis, DIY heuristics, magic numbers among others. 

Press 'h' to switch between high/low resolution pixel density (set to low for mobiles)

Touch to listen

metadata.name: Letter #266
metadata.description:
This is a letter from the computer to you by asemic writing. Imagine what message is written on it.

The artwork is inspired from Shodo(Êõ∏ÈÅì) that is known as Japanese calligraphy.
Shodo is the way of writing Kanji and Kana characters with a brush in India ink.
It's one of the traditional Japanese arts.

Paper Color and Ink Color combinations has 18 variations.
Aspect Ratio has 5 variations.
Font Size has 3 variations.
Font Weight has 3 variations.
Font Style has 3 variations.
Each character is randomly generated by a mathematical algorithm.

- Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
- Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel  (wait a minutes)

metadata.name: Ode to Random #133
metadata.description:
This simple minimalist generative token is a tribute to randomness. The underlying grid, the start and end of the colored shapes, the color styles, the transitioning point from order to chaos, are randomized. The names behind the Styles of this token are derived from artists who have greatly inspired me, all or most of whom have incorporated randomness or chaos in their art in one way or another.

The price and number of editions were also chosen using a pseudorandom number generator.

Embrace the random!

Made in p5js
Created December 2021
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Artifact #319
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Magic Board #100
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Glitchy Masks #13
metadata.description:
A big thank you to Aleksandra from https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Aleksandra for their assistance with the code!

In this project, I explored the concept of randomness and was pleasantly surprised by the results. After a few iterations, masks began to emerge. I added a mirroring effect to enhance the visual and added eyes for added realism. The end result is a series of intriguing masks, created through the use of randomness and artistic experimentation.

To save your canvas, simply press S.

For more information and to stay up to date with my work, follow me on Twitter at @lomzart or visit my portfolio website at lomz.net. Thank you for your interest!

metadata.name: Gentrax EP #170
metadata.description:
Gentrax EP is a generative audiovisual artwork. Each iteration produces a generative house/garage track ~3 minutes in length while drawing out accompanying artwork. Live piece is aspect ratio agnostic and scales to any window size, but an aspect of 1:1.414 is preferred and can be set with an URL parameter.

Audio controls:
1-7: Channel mutes/unmutes
a: Filter up 
z: Filter down
c: Flanger on/off
v: Reverb (cycle thru three settings)
q: Switch bassline octave&seq (cycle thru three settings)
b: Portamento on/off

Visual controls: 
p: Fast forward to final artwork
o: Save canvas

Url parameters: 
&w=800 : Set width of canvas. If aspect ratio is not defined, artwork will be in preferred aspect ratio (1.41414)
&a=1.5 : Set aspect ratio. number <1 = Wide canvas
&wl=1 : Locks canvas aspect ratio to preferred 


made with p5.js & tone.js
Using tonejs synthesis for bass plus oneshot samples from various drum machines & Alpha Juno 2
<3

CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Glossolalia #235
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It‚Äôs less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù to the url to double the size, ‚Äú&density=3‚Äù to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append ‚Äú&grain=##‚Äù to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: System Œ≤ #230
metadata.description:
Œ± -> Œ≤ is about "Increases in magnitude and decreases in computation". And still related the fleeting time in the generating process.

My role in this work is more of a discoverer than a creator. 

Try to reveal the possibilities of time perception in the generative art through negotiating with incomprehensible mathematical equations.

What I want to explore through this work is that behind the generated results, the dynamic process of generations are equally diverse and unpredictable.

When we watch the generating process displayed on the computer, changing instantly, moving, multiplying, disappearing, and we hesitate, wonder, pause, await, as if many possibilities of time perception have emerged in the fragmented moments.

_

press [2] -> Œ≤‚Å∞„ÄÄ

metadata.name: Anachronous #141
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins ¬∑ Lyon, 2022
